@michaelwoerister: Sure thing.

#### What we do want to lint

What we want to lint against are cases where the reference does or might leak.  So, e.g., we want this to lint:

```rust
struct W(u8);
impl W {
    fn leak(&self) -> &Self {
        self
    }
}

fn leak() -> &'static W {
    static mut X: W = W(0);
    unsafe { X.leak() }
    //~^ WARN/DENY
}
```

That is, we want to lint when a potentially long-lived reference (or mutable reference) to a `static mut` is created, even if that creation is "hidden" via autoref.

#### What we don't need to lint

In the back and forth, we had earlier asked @obeis to lint about cases like this:

```rust
static mut X: u8 = 0;
unsafe { X += 1 };
```

...because `AddAssign::add_assign` takes `self` by mutable reference.  But we've since worked out that we don't need to lint those cases, and that it's preferable to not lint them because we don't want to push people to write instead:

```rust
static mut X: u8 = 0;
unsafe { X = X + 1 };
```

...since that has no more and no less UB than the first example.

In general, anywhere that we can prove that the reference is short-lived, either because we're not actually creating a reference in the MIR or because the signature guarantees the reference isn't leaked, as with `AddAssign::add_assign`, does not need to lint.  So, e.g., all of the cases covered in this comment do not need to lint:

- https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/pull/124895#discussion_r1706180522

(False positives are OK.  Anywhere that it's too hard to prove that the reference doesn't leak, it's OK to lint.)

#### Lint rather than hard error

In discussing this on the lang call, we reevaluated whether this actually met our standard for a hard error and decided that it did not.  So, for all cases of references to mutable statics (includes the non-hidden ones), we want to max out at `deny-by-default` in Rust 2024 rather than issuing a hard error.  In earlier editions it will be `warn-by-default` as it already is in the PR.

---

